The article pays tribute to Carl Levin, who served in the United States Senate for thirty years. The author describes Levin as honorable, decent, brilliant, humble, and principled. Levin earned the trust of his constituents and colleagues through hard work, detailed study of the issues, and forging consensus. He was known for looking people in the eye, listening with an open mind, and responding respectfully. As chairman and ranking member of the Armed Services Committee, Levin protected national security, upheld values, and honored the service of military members. He also advocated for the American worker and the auto industry, especially during the Great Recession. Levin fought for education, gun safety, corporate accountability, and more. The author recalls their shared commitment to civil rights and their discussions about family and Michigan. The article concludes with condolences to Levin's family and recognition of his legacy as a great American.